Preheat your oven to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7. Chop the @sweet potato{2}(chopped into 2cm chunks) (no need to peel).

Put the sweet potato chunks onto a large #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil{drizzle}, season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, then toss to coat. Spread out in a single layer.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden, ~{25-35%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

In the meantime, pour the @water{300%ml} for the rice into a medium #saucepan{} with a #tight-fitting lid{}.

Stir in the @jasmine rice{150%g} and @salt{1/4%tsp} and bring to the boil. Once boiling, turn the heat down to medium and cover with the lid.

Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Meanwhile, zest and quarter the @lime{1}.

Peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2} (or use a #garlic press{}).

== Thai Curry ==

Heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a large #frying pan{} on medium heat.

Add the garlic and @red Thai style paste{50%g} to the pan. Fry until fragrant, ~{1%minute}.

Stir in the @coconut milk{180%ml}, @soy sauce{15%ml}, @sugar{1%tsp} and @water{100%ml} for the sauce. Bring to the boil, then reduce the heat and simmer until slightly thickened, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Taste and season with @salt{} and @pepper{} if needed.

Stir in the @peas{120%g} and add the @baby spinach{40%g} to the pan a handful at a time until wilted and piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}. Remove from the heat.

When the sweet potato is ready, stir it into the curry. Reheat if necessary, then remove from the heat and stir in a good squeeze of lime juice.

When the rice is ready, fluff it up with a #fork{}. Stir through the lime zest.

Share the zesty rice between your #serving bowls{}.

Spoon over the Thai style curry to finish.

Serve any remaining lime wedges alongside for squeezing over.

Enjoy!